Aura Inc — Economy & Progression Design

Core Philosophy

The game should reward all three player types fairly without any one style completely dominating:

Active players — clicking constantly, chasing Legendary rolls, high volume shipping
Passive/AFK players — letting cubes mutate over time, maximizing value per cube, big infrequent payouts
Macro/Long session players — acceptable advantage but capped so free casual players aren't completely left behind

Cube Mutation System (Option C — Confirmed Direction)

Cubes sitting in the habitat increase in value over time rather than earning direct passive cash.

Mutation Tiers Over Time


Key Rules

Mutation applies on TOP of the spawned tier — a lucky Epic that sits for 10 min becomes even more valuable
Legendary cubes cannot mutate further in tier but still gain value bonuses over time
Platform payout reflects the current mutated value of collected cubes, not the spawn value
Cubes that get collected by a platform take their current mutation value with them

Active vs Passive Balance

Active Player Loop

Click fast → high volume of cubes → more chances at rare RNG rolls → ship frequently for steady income
Upgrades: Drop Rate, Block Value, Platform Capacity, Ship Interval reduction
Reward: More cubes = more lottery tickets for Legendary spawns

Passive/AFK Player Loop

Let cubes sit and mutate → fewer but much higher value cubes → infrequent massive payouts
Upgrades: Mutation Speed, Mutation Tier Chance, Habitat Capacity (hold more cubes longer)
Reward: A box full of mutated Epics and Legendaries is worth far more than fresh Commons

Why Neither Dominates

Active players ship more often but at lower average cube value
Passive players ship rarely but at much higher average cube value
Total earnings over time should be roughly equal with different upgrade paths
Both feel satisfying in different ways — active is exciting, passive is rewarding

AFK / Macro Abuse Prevention

The Problem

AFK players leaving devices on 24/7 would accumulate mutated Legendaries non-stop
Macro players auto-clicking would generate unlimited high-volume shipping income
This creates an unbridgeable gap between casual and hardcore players

The Solution — Diminishing Returns Over Time

Inspired by Egg Inc's offline earnings cap:

Mutation speed slows down significantly after 30 minutes of inactivity
First 30 min: full mutation speed
30 min to 2 hours: 50% mutation speed
2+ hours: 10% mutation speed (nearly stopped)
This means AFK overnight gives maybe 3-4x the value of a 30 min session, not 20x
Habitat has a hard capacity cap
Once the habitat is full, no new cubes can spawn and mutation stops
Forces even AFK players to check in and ship occasionally
Upgrading habitat capacity is a meaningful choice — more room = longer AFK sessions
Macro protection — server-side rate limiting already in place
AdminConfig.FireRate enforced server-side so macros clicking faster than the cap get ignored
Consider adding a per-session click diminishing return (after 10 min of continuous clicking, drop rate reduces slightly)

Piggy Bank System (Monetization)

The Problem with Egg Inc's Version

Breaking the piggy bank gives too large an advantage
Free players feel like they can never catch up to paying players
The gap compounds over time as paying players use their advantage to progress faster

Aura Inc's Version — Friendlier Piggy Bank

The piggy bank fills passively over time just by playing (not just by paying)
Free players can break it too — it just takes longer to fill without premium
Premium players get a bigger bank and it fills faster — meaningful advantage but not game-breaking


Key Rules

Free bank breaks should feel genuinely rewarding — not a consolation prize
Premium bank should never give more than ~3-4x the free bank value at equivalent play time
No pay-to-win on core mechanics (drop rates, mutation speed) — cosmetics and QoL only for Robux

